title: Measurement of cumulative cross sections for 232Th fission products upon irradiation with medium-energy 3He nuclei

x4freetext: Measurement of cumulative cross sections for 232Th
fission products upon irradiation with medium-energy
3He nuclei

x4codes.shortRef: Jour: Physics of Atomic Nuclei, Vol.85, p.1449 (2022)

x4freetext: English translation
Original text was published in the journal "Yadernaya
Fizika i Inzhiniring", Vol. 13, No. 5, p. 421, 2022.
U-150 cyclotron
The targets obtained using sedimentation method were
mechanically stable and visually uniformly thick
layers of thorium dioxide with thicknesses of 7-11
mg/cm2. The applied spot diameter was 20 mm.
A mean current was 0.1 mu-A, total charge of ~0.3 mu-Ah
The peak areas of the total absorption of
gamma quanta were measured using an ORTEC GEM gamma
spectrometer with an ultrapure germanium detector.
During the measurements, the targets were located at
a distance of 6-40 cm above the detector surface
depending on the load of the spectrometer. The dead
time during measurements did not exceed 5%.
The exposure time for each fission fragment
significantly exceeded the decay time of its
short-lived precursors after the end of irradiation.
Therefore, the assumption of complete decay of the
precursors by the end of irradiation was made by
reducing the measured activity of fission fragments
to the end of irradiation.
The foil stack contained 11 targets. Charged
particle moderators in the form of aluminum foils with
thicknesses of 9 and 30 mu-m were placed between the
targets in the stack.
Calculated corrections for the decay of the
radionuclide during the measurement time and
self-absorption of gamma-quanta in the targets were
introduced.
The errors of the measured values include:
the error in determining the detector
efficiency;
the errors in determination of peak
areas of the total absorption of gamma quanta in the
instrument spectra;
the error of quantum yield.
Entry was approved by Dr. V.A.Zagryadskiy.
99Mo was detected via 99mTc decay
112Pd was detected via 112AG decay
